Preheat your oven to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Halve the @baking potato{2}(halved lengthways) and pop them onto a #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, then season with @salt and @pepper{}.

Sprinkle over the @north Indian style spice mix{1} and rub it all over the potatoes. Lay them, cut-side down, on the baking tray.

When the oven is hot, bake on the top shelf until tender and a knife slips in easily, ~{30-40%minutes}.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim the @green beans{150%g}.

Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%400g can} in a #sieve{}.

When the potatoes have baked for ~{10%minutes}, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the garlic and @korma curry paste{50%g}. Fry for ~{1-2%minutes}.

Meanwhile, boil a half-full #kettle{}.

Add the chickpeas, @creme fraiche{75%g}, @vegetable stock paste{10}, @water{75%ml}(for the sauce), and @salt and @pepper to the pan. Stir well and season with @salt and @pepper.

Bring to the boil, then lower to a simmer. Cook, stirring occasionally, for ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add the @baby spinach{40%g} to the pan a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}, then stir through half the @mango chutney{40%g}.

While the curried chickpeas simmer, pour the boiled water from your kettle into a saucepan with @salt{1/2%tsp} on high heat.

Bring back to the boil, then add the green beans and cook until just tender, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{}, then return to the saucepan. Season with @salt and @pepper. Toss in @butter{} (if you have any).

When everything's ready, transfer your baked potatoes to your plates.

Gently mash the cut sides of the potatoes with a #fork{} and add some @butter{} (if you have any).

Top with your curried chickpeas, @toasted flaked almonds{15%g} and spoon over the remaining mango chutney.

Serve the green beans alongside. Enjoy!